{% markdown %}
Rather than wiring up bespoke flexbox or grid for every section of your app, drop in a named layout like [`wa-stack`](/docs/utilities/stack), [`wa-cluster`](/docs/utilities/cluster), [`wa-split`](/docs/utilities/split), [`wa-flank`](/docs/utilities/flank), [`wa-frame`](/docs/utilities/frame), or [`wa-grid`](/docs/utilities/grid) and let it do the heavy lifting. Each layout is responsive out of the box, adapts fluidly to its container (not the viewport), and composes cleanly with the others.

For finer control, the same set also includes property-level helpers for [gap](/docs/utilities/gap), [align-items](/docs/utilities/align-items), [justify-content](/docs/utilities/justify-content), and [flex-wrap](/docs/utilities/flex-wrap), so you can tweak individual layouts without resorting to custom CSS.

## Adding to Your Project

Layout utilities are bundled with Web Awesome's [style utilities](/docs/utilities) — if you've already installed style utilities, `wa-stack`, `wa-grid`, and the rest are ready to use. If you haven't yet, the tabs below will get you set up in under a minute.
{% endmarkdown %}

